<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-409-251  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 409 251.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  August 20 1990 v4 n30 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sandia tackles biometric inertia. (Sandia National Laboratories'Safeguards and Security Group evaluates biometric verifiers andother entry monitoring devices)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Richardson, Jennifer.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sandia National Laboratories' Safeguards and Security Groupevaluates entry monitoring devices, including biometric verifiers,and proposes security measures for several government agencies,including the US Energy Department, which sponsors its research.andO;Sandia recently evaluated six types of biometric devices,including devices that recognize an authorized user's voice,fingerprints, handprints, signatures and retinal patterns, andfound that prices must come down before they will be useful forfederal agencies.andP;  One hundred Sandia employees attempted tolegally and illegally log onto several machines, with the speedand accuracy of the various devices in detecting an unauthorizeduser analyzed; both false rejections and false acceptances wereconsidered.andP;  Sandia found that the easiest and fastest method washand geometry: retinal scan and fingerprint identification werethe most accurate.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BiometricsAccess ControlsSecurity SystemsTestingGovernment AgencyNational GovernmentComparisonSandia Laboratories.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>